A:

I think you're confusing the word "layer" and the word "part".
"Layer" is a metaphorical term to describe something that is continuous and continuous.  "Part" is a word to describe a discrete entity.
If you take the word "layer" as you are using it: it refers to a continuous entity.  The word "part" is a term that refers to a discrete entity.
Since you are referring to a layer of K8s, this is what I think you are talking about.

Q:

How to write a function to replace all occurences of a string with a predefined string in JavaScript?

I have two strings, both of which will have newlines in them.
The first string will be read from a file, and the second string will be a variable.
I need to replace each instance of a string (in this case "My Text") with a string (in this case "My Text.newline")
I am using the following code (which is in mocha):
function replace (str, newline, obj) {
    // First we iterate over the source string
    str = str.replace(/\r\n/g, function (match) {
        return newline;
    });

    return str;
}

replace("Hello World", "\n", "This is my text\n");

Live example

A:

You can use RegExp to achieve this:

const replace = (str, newline, obj) => {
    const result = new RegExp(/\r\n\w+/g, 'g');
    return str.replace(result, newline);
};

console.log(replace("Hello World", "\n", "This is my text\n"));

